{{Infobox ancient site | name = Nonaka Kofun | native_name = 野中古墳 | location = [[:en:Fujiidera|Fujiidera, Osaka]], [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]], Japan | coordinates = {{coord|34|33|36.9|N|135|36|9.3|E|display=inline,title}} | region = Japan | type = {{ill|Square tumulus (Hōfun)|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Square tumulus (Hōfun)|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} | length = 37m per side | built = 5th century | burial = Wooden coffin, wooden chest | burial goods = Armor, iron weapons | designation1 = National [[Historic Site of Japan|Historic Site]] (part of the [[:en:Furuichi Kofun Cluster|Furuichi Kofun Group]]) | map = Japan Osaka | map_caption = location in Osaka Prefecture | image = {{image requested|cat=Fujiidera, Osaka}} }} '''Nonaka Kofun''' (野中古墳) is a mid-[[Kofun period]] Kofun ([[kofun]]) located in [[:en:Fujiidera|Fujidera]], [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]], Japan. A significant number of iron weapons, armor, and [[:en:Sue pottery|Sue pottery]] have been excavated from the site. The kofun is designation1 as a part of the [[UNESCO]] [[World Historic Site]] "Ancient Kofun Clusters," specifically within the [[:en:Furuichi Kofun Cluster|Furuichi Kofun Cluster]]. It is also a [[National Historic Site of Japan]].
== Overview == The Nonaka Kofun is part of the [[:en:Furuichi Kofun Cluster|Furuichi Kofun Cluster]] and is situated north of the rear circle of the {{ill|Makasuyama Kofun|ja|墓山古墳|1=Hakayama Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Makasuyama Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakayama Kofun|qq=}}, leading to speculation that it may have served as a {{ill|Baizuka|ja|陪塚|subsidiary Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baizuka|qq=}} for the latter.<ref name="yomiuri140212">"Restoration Completed for Nonaka Kofun Armor," ''Yomiuri Shimbun,'' February 12, 2014.</ref>
The mound is a square-shaped tumulus (方墳) built in two tiers, with each side measuring 37 meters and a height of 4 meters. It features a surrounding moat, [[:en:Fukiishi|fukiishi]] (roofing stones), cylindrical haniwa rows, and figurative haniwa, including helmets, "Kinugasa" lids, and horned helmets (衝角付冑). Numerous [[:en:Sue pottery|Sue pottery]] and [[:en:Haji pottery|Haji pottery]] were excavated from the mound's summit.<ref name="yomiuri140212"/>
Beneath the mound's summit, five sets of burial facilities were aligned in parallel, consisting of wooden coffins and wooden chests. Only the second wooden coffin is believed to have contained human remains, while the other four are interpreted as dedicated for grave goods. These facilities yielded a significant collection of grave goods, including: * 11 sets of iron armor ([[tankō]] 短甲) * 11 helmets (冑) * Components such as grass skirts and shoulder guards * Iron swords (鉄刀), iron spears (鉄剣), and a large number of iron arrowheads (鉄鏃).
The abundant iron burial goods, Sue pottery, and weapons provide invaluable insights into the burial practices of the mid-Kofun period. The tumulus is estimated to have been built during the early to mid-5th century.
== Excavations and Preservation == In 1964, an excavation led by [[:en:Osaka University|Osaka University]] unearthed approximately 2,000 burial goods.<ref>"Crowdfunding Advances for 3D Digitalization of Important burial goods," ''Yomiuri Shimbun,'' December 22, 2018.</ref> The site was designation1 as a National Historic Site in 1995 and incorporated into the unified designation of the "Furuichi Kofun Cluster" in 2001. The iron armor and other burial goods are stored at Osaka University and were designation1 as [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]] of Japan in 2015.<ref>"Osaka City Art Museum Registered as Cultural Property," ''Yomiuri Shimbun,'' March 15, 2015.</ref>
Additionally, a 1964 color film documenting the excavation was rediscovered in 2009.<ref>"1964 Nonaka Kofun Excavation Film Found," ''Yomiuri Shimbun,'' December 24, 2012.</ref>
